    moduleKey: "foundations",
    kicker: "Foundations",
    dek: `For a century, the aerial shot was the most expensive tool in the filmmaker's kit — a helicopter, a pilot, a gyro-stabilized camera, and a budget most films never had. Then a folding drone put that exact shot in a backpack for the price of a used lens. This is one of the biggest democratizations in the history of the medium. Here's what it means for you.`,
    seoTitle: "Why Drones Changed Cinematography: Drone Filmmaking | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Drone filmmaking put a helicopter shot in a backpack. A working filmmaker on how drones democratized aerial cinematography, what they do brilliantly, and where they don't belong. Chapter 1 of Drone Cinematography.",
    body: `<p>Think about what an aerial shot used to require. To rise up off an actor and reveal the landscape behind them, or to sweep over a coastline, a filmmaker needed to charter a helicopter, hire a specialist aerial operator, mount a stabilized camera system worth more than most people's cars, and burn a day of good weather — all for a handful of shots. It was the exclusive language of studio films, and if you were making something small, the aerial shot simply wasn't available to you. It sat behind a wall of money. The drone knocked that wall down. Now the same rising reveal costs a battery charge and fifteen minutes, and a first-time filmmaker can put a shot in their movie that used to signal a multi-million-dollar budget. That's the revolution, and it's why "drone filmmaking" went from a novelty to a standard part of the toolkit in barely a decade.</p>

<h2>What a drone does brilliantly</h2>

<p>Understanding a drone's real strengths tells you when to reach for it — and stops you using it just because you own one. A drone gives you:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>The reveal.</b> Rising and tilting to uncover a landscape, a city, or a character's place in a bigger world. The single most powerful and recognizable aerial move.</li>
  <li><b>Scale and geography.</b> One shot that shows how big a place is, or where things sit in relation to each other — context an eye-level camera can't give.</li>
  <li><b>Impossible camera moves.</b> Gliding over water, through a canyon, alongside a moving car, or straight up a cliff face — motion no crane, dolly, or Steadicam can match.</li>
  <li><b>Production value, instantly.</b> A single well-flown aerial makes a small film feel bigger and more expensive. It's the cheapest "we have a budget" signal you can buy.</li>
  <li><b>Access to the unreachable.</b> Over a crowd, above a forest, out across a lake — vantage points that used to need a crane, a helicopter, or permission you'd never get.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Powerful, not magic — and heavily regulated</h2>

<p>Here's the honest counterweight, and it runs through this whole course: a drone is a powerful specialty tool, not a fix-everything camera, and it comes with real responsibilities that a phone or a DSLR never did. Two cautions matter from the start. First, the aerial shot is <em>seasoning, not the meal</em>. Because drones are cheap and fun, beginners tend to open every project with a swooping aerial and drop in five more for no reason, and it quickly reads as a demo reel rather than a film. A great aerial shot is used sparingly and with purpose — to reveal, to establish, to punctuate — and one well-placed aerial is worth more than a dozen aimless flyovers. We'll come back to that discipline in Chapter 10. Second, and more seriously, <strong>flying a drone is a regulated activity with real legal weight</strong>. Unlike picking up a camera, putting an aircraft in the sky is governed by aviation law — registration, pilot certification, airspace restrictions, and rules about where and how you can fly, especially the moment money is involved. Ignore that and you're not risking a bad shot; you're risking fines and worse. This is genuinely different from every other course in this program, and it's why an entire early chapter is devoted to the law. So come in excited — the drone really has handed you a tool filmmakers used to only dream about — but come in respectful. Treat it as an aircraft and a specialty instrument, learn to fly it well and legally, and use its shots with restraint, and it will add production value to your films that used to be reserved for the studios. That's the promise of this course, and the rest of it is how to deliver on it safely.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The aerial shot used to sit behind a wall of money. The drone knocked that wall down — now the same shot costs a battery charge and fifteen minutes.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>The first drone shot I ever landed in a film was a slow rise off two actors to reveal the empty valley they were standing in — a shot that, twenty years earlier, I simply could not have afforded. Watching it play back, I understood why drones changed everything: it wasn't just a cool angle, it was a whole grammar of shots that used to be locked away from small filmmakers. But I also learned fast that the temptation is to overuse it. Now I ask one question before every flight — "does this shot earn its place, or am I just flying because I can?" Fly with purpose, fly legally, and the drone is the biggest bang for your buck in filmmaking.</p>
</div>`,
