    kicker: "Foundations",
    dek: `Drone marketing is a blizzard of specs — resolution, sensor size, transmission range, obstacle sensors, weight classes. Most of it doesn't matter for your footage, and one number you might overlook — the weight — quietly decides which laws you have to follow. Here's how to cut through the noise and pick the right drone for filmmaking.`,
    seoTitle: "Choosing Your Camera Drone for Filmmaking | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "How to choose a camera drone for filmmaking — sensor size, log recording, obstacle sensing, weight classes, and what the specs actually mean for your footage. A working filmmaker's buying guide. Chapter 2 of Drone Cinematography.",
    body: `<p>A camera drone is really two products fused together: a flying machine and a camera. When you buy one, you're choosing both at once, and the trick is knowing which specs affect the <em>image</em> and which affect the <em>flying</em> — because they're not the same, and the marketing blurs them on purpose. Just as importantly, before you fall in love with any model, look at one unglamorous number that has nothing to do with picture quality: the <strong>weight</strong>. Drone regulations around the world are built around weight thresholds, and a lighter drone often sits in a simpler, less restrictive category. A drone that's a little worse on paper but drops under a key weight limit can be far more <em>useful</em> to you, because it's easier to fly legally. We'll dig into the law next chapter; just know now that weight is a buying decision, not only a spec.</p>

<h2>The specs that actually matter</h2>

<p>Cut through the datasheet with these, roughly in order of importance for filmmaking:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Weight class.</b> Which legal category the drone falls into (this varies by country). A lighter drone can mean simpler rules — check this before anything else.</li>
  <li><b>Sensor size and log.</b> A larger sensor gives better dynamic range and low-light performance, and a drone that records a flat/log profile grades far better — the same "capture flat, decide later" logic as any camera.</li>
  <li><b>Codec and bitrate.</b> Higher-bitrate recording (and formats beyond basic compressed video) hold up in the grade. Cheaper drones bake in a contrasty look that's hard to fix.</li>
  <li><b>Flight time and spare batteries.</b> Most drones fly 20–40 minutes on a battery. Buy several batteries — your real "flight time" is however many packs you own, and you'll always want more.</li>
  <li><b>Obstacle sensing and stability.</b> Sensors that detect obstacles and hold a rock-steady hover in wind make you a safer, smoother pilot. Genuinely worth having, especially while you learn.</li>
  <li><b>Transmission range and reliability.</b> A solid video link that doesn't drop matters more than a huge advertised range you'll rarely (and often can't legally) use.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Buy for the films you'll actually make</h2>

<p>The honest advice is to resist buying the biggest, most cinematic drone you can afford, and instead buy the one that matches the flying you'll realistically do. The pro-level heavy drones carry larger sensors and interchangeable lenses and produce genuinely superior images — but they're expensive, they demand more skill, they fall into stricter legal categories, and they're a lot of aircraft to crash while you're learning. For most filmmakers starting out, a capable consumer or "prosumer" drone that shoots a gradeable image, sits in a friendly weight class, and is forgiving to fly will get you shots indistinguishable from the big rigs in a finished, graded film. It's the same principle from every gear chapter in this program: the limitation on your aerials won't be the drone, it'll be your flying and your eye. A cheaper drone you fly confidently and legally beats an expensive one you're scared to launch. And there's a real learning-curve argument for starting smaller and lighter: your first drone is the one you're most likely to crash, misjudge, or fly into a branch, and that lesson is much cheaper on an affordable aircraft than on a flagship. Get something that flies well, records flat, and keeps you in a simple legal category; learn to fly it beautifully; and upgrade later only when a specific project actually needs more camera than it can give. Buy for the films you're making now, not the ones you imagine making someday.</p>

<div class="pullquote">A drone that's slightly worse on paper but drops under a key weight limit can be far more useful — because it's easier to fly legally.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My first drone was a modest one, and I'm glad — because I flew it into a tree in the first week. If that had been a flagship, it would have been a very expensive lesson. That little drone taught me to fly, shot aerials that made it into real films, and stayed in the simplest legal category so I could actually use it. When I finally upgraded, it was because a specific job needed a bigger sensor, not because a review told me to. Buy the drone that fits your flying and your law, learn it cold, and let the projects tell you when it's time for more.</p>
</div>`,
