    moduleKey: "foundations",
    kicker: "Foundations",
    dek: `This is the chapter that has no equivalent in the rest of this program — because a drone isn't just a camera, it's an aircraft, and putting an aircraft in the sky is governed by aviation law. Get this wrong and you're not looking at a bad shot; you're looking at fines and liability. The specifics vary by country, so this chapter teaches you the categories of rules you must go and confirm for where you fly.`,
    seoTitle: "Drone Law for Filmmakers: Licensing & Registration | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "The law every drone filmmaker must know — registration, pilot certification for commercial work, airspace rules, and why the moment money is involved everything changes. A working filmmaker's plain-English guide. Chapter 3 of Drone Cinematography.",
    body: `<p>Let me be blunt, because this matters: the aviation authority in your country regulates drones, and the rules are real, enforceable, and different depending on where you are — the FAA in the United States, EASA across much of Europe, the CAA in the UK, and so on. This chapter cannot give you the exact rule for your location, and any course that claims to would be doing you a disservice, because these regulations change and vary. What this chapter <em>can</em> do is tell you the categories of obligation that exist almost everywhere, so you know what to go and check with your local authority before you ever launch — and so you understand the single most important line in all of drone law for a filmmaker: <strong>the rules get much stricter the moment your flying is commercial.</strong></p>

<h2>The obligations to confirm for your country</h2>

<p>Nearly every jurisdiction has some version of these. Treat this as your checklist of things to look up and comply with locally:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Registration.</b> Most countries require you to register your drone (usually above a small weight) and mark it with your registration number. Cheap, quick, and mandatory — do it first.</li>
  <li><b>Pilot certification.</b> Flying for any commercial purpose — which includes almost all filmmaking — typically requires you to pass a test and hold a remote-pilot certificate (in the US, the FAA Part 107). Recreational flying has lighter requirements; paid or professional work does not.</li>
  <li><b>Airspace rules.</b> You cannot fly wherever you like. Controlled airspace near airports, restricted zones, and no-fly areas require authorization or are simply off-limits. Apps and official maps show you the airspace before you fly.</li>
  <li><b>Operating limits.</b> Common rules include keeping the drone within visual line of sight, below a maximum altitude, away from crowds and people who aren't part of the production, and not flying at night without specific permission.</li>
  <li><b>Location permissions.</b> Beyond airspace, the land or property you fly over and take off from may need permission — national parks, private property, and city jurisdictions often have their own rules on top of aviation law.</li>
  <li><b>Insurance.</b> For professional work, liability insurance is often required or strongly advisable, and clients and locations will frequently ask for proof of it.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The commercial line changes everything</h2>

<p>Here's the distinction that trips up filmmakers, so let's make it unmissable: the law usually treats flying for fun very differently from flying for <em>any</em> professional or commercial reason — and filmmaking almost always counts as commercial. This isn't about whether you personally got paid for a specific flight. If you're shooting footage for a film, a client, a portfolio meant to win work, or anything with a professional purpose, most authorities consider that commercial operation, and it triggers the stricter tier: the pilot certificate, the insurance, the tighter operating rules. The hobbyist exemption you might have used to fly your drone around a park does not cover you the moment you're capturing shots for a production. Filmmakers get caught out by exactly this — they assume that because they flew fine as a hobbyist, they're fine on a shoot, and they're not. So before you put a drone in the sky for any film work, do three things: <strong>register the aircraft, get certified as a commercial remote pilot for your country, and check the airspace and location permissions for every single shoot.</strong> None of this is optional, and none of it is as hard as it sounds — the certification is a studyable test, the registration is a form, and the airspace check is an app. Do them once (and the airspace check every time), and you fly legally, insured, and without the low-grade dread of the pilot who knows they're cutting corners. Skip them, and one incident — a drone that hits someone, strays near an airport, or drops out of the sky over a crowd — turns a cheap tool into the most expensive mistake of your career. The whole rest of this course assumes you've squared away this chapter. Fly legal, and everything else is just craft.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The hobbyist rules you used to fly around a park do not cover you the moment you're capturing shots for a production. Filmmaking is commercial flying.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I treat the legal side of drone work exactly like I treat insurance and releases on any shoot: boring, non-negotiable, and the thing that lets me sleep. Before any aerial day, I confirm the aircraft's registered, my certification is current, I've checked the airspace for that exact location, and I've got permission to take off and land where I'm standing. It takes an afternoon to get certified and two minutes to check airspace on the day. That small discipline is the difference between a professional drone operator and a liability waiting to happen. Please — get legal before you get creative.</p>
</div>`,
