    body: `<p>Here's the reassuring news: you don't need dozens of moves. Almost all cinematic aerial footage is built from a small, repeatable set of camera moves, and once you can fly each one smoothly (Chapter 5), you have the vocabulary to shoot most of what a film asks for. But treat these as more than tricks. Each move carries a meaning — a reveal creates awe, an orbit builds importance, a top-down feels detached and godlike. When you choose a move, you're choosing what the shot <em>says</em>, so learn both the flying and the feeling. Fly them all slowly; every one of these looks more cinematic the slower and more deliberate it is.</p>

<h2>The essential drone moves</h2>

<p>Master these and you've got a working aerial toolkit:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>The reveal.</b> Rising and/or tilting the camera up to uncover a vista behind a foreground subject or object. The signature drone move — it delivers awe and scale, and it's the one you'll use most.</li>
  <li><b>The orbit.</b> Circling around a subject while keeping it centered. It makes the subject feel important and monumental, and shows it from every side. Combine a slow sideways drift with a gentle rotate.</li>
  <li><b>The fly-through / push-in.</b> Gliding forward toward or past a subject — through a gap, over a road, toward a building. It creates momentum and draws the viewer into the space.</li>
  <li><b>The top-down (bird's eye).</b> Camera pointed straight down, looking at the world as pattern and geometry. Feels detached, observational, and graphic — great for revealing shape and scale abstractly.</li>
  <li><b>The follow (chase).</b> Tracking a moving subject — a car, a runner, a boat — keeping pace with it. It puts energy and motion into the frame and ties the aerial to the action.</li>
  <li><b>The fly-away / pull-back.</b> Reversing out and up, away from a subject, shrinking them into their surroundings. A natural ending shot — it says "and so we leave them" and reveals how small they are in the world.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Moves are words — build sentences with intent</h2>

<p>Once you can fly these, the real skill is choosing the <em>right</em> one for the moment, because each is a word in a language and you're using them to say something. A reveal that lifts to expose a vast landscape behind a lone figure says "look how big this world is, how small they are." An orbit that circles a hero holding their ground says "this person, this place, matters." A top-down over a city says "here is the pattern of human life from above, detached and vast." A pull-back that flies away and up as a story ends says "we're letting go now." When you match the move to the meaning, the aerial stops being decoration and becomes storytelling — it does emotional work no eye-level shot can. The failure mode, which we'll hit hard in Chapter 10, is choosing moves for how impressive they look rather than what they say, stacking swoops and orbits and reveals with no thought to meaning until the footage feels like a showreel instead of a film. So as you learn each move, learn its feeling alongside its flying. Ask, before every aerial: what does this shot need to <em>say</em> — awe, importance, momentum, detachment, farewell — and which move says it? Fly that one, slowly and cleanly, and skip the rest. A film with three perfectly chosen aerial moves, each doing real emotional work, will always beat one drowning in a dozen impressive-but-empty flyovers. Learn the vocabulary, then use it like a writer choosing words: deliberately, sparingly, and always in service of what you're trying to say.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Each move is a word — a reveal says awe, an orbit says importance, a pull-back says farewell. Choosing a move is choosing what the shot says.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>Early on I flew moves because they looked cool — a swoop here, an orbit there, reveals everywhere. The footage was impressive and meant nothing. The shift came when I started asking what each shot needed to say. Now I'll fly a slow reveal because the scene needs to feel the character's smallness, or a pull-back because the story is ending and we're letting go. Same moves, completely different films. Learn the six moves, then forget about impressing anyone and just ask what the shot is trying to say. The move you need is usually the quiet, obvious one.</p>
</div>`,
    takeaways: [
      `Almost all aerial footage is built from a few moves: reveal, orbit, fly-through, top-down, follow, and pull-back.`,
      `Each move carries meaning — awe, importance, momentum, detachment, energy, farewell — so choosing a move chooses what the shot says.`,
      `Fly every move slowly and deliberately; they all read more cinematic the more controlled and unhurried they are.`,
      `Match the move to the meaning — three purposeful aerials beat a dozen impressive-but-empty flyovers.`
    ]
