    time: "8 min",
    moduleKey: "apply",
    kicker: "Putting It to Work",
    dek: `Aerial footage arrives with two special challenges in the edit: it tends to be long and slow, and it often doesn't match the color of your ground footage. Solve both — trim ruthlessly, grade to match, and pace it right — and your drone shots stop announcing themselves and simply become part of the film. Here's how to finish your aerials.`,
    seoTitle: "Editing & Grading Drone Footage into Your Film | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "How to edit and grade drone footage — trimming into the good part of a move, matching aerials to your ground footage in the grade, warp stabilization, and pacing aerial shots. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 11 of Drone Cinematography.",
    body: `<p>Everything from the Editing courses applies here — edit for story, back up your footage, correct before you stylize — but aerials have two quirks that catch people out. First, drone clips are usually long and slow: you'll have a thirty-second glide where only the best eight seconds are magic, and the beginner's instinct is to use the whole thing because it's beautiful and it took a battery to get. Second, drone cameras have different sensors and color science than your main camera, so an aerial dropped straight into a scene often looks noticeably different — cooler, more contrasty, more saturated — and sticks out. The edit is where you fix both: <strong>trim aerials down to only their strongest moment, and grade them to match the film around them.</strong> Do that and the audience never notices the shot came from a drone; they just feel the film.</p>

<h2>Finishing your aerials</h2>

<p>The workflow for making drone footage sit properly in your film:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Trim ruthlessly to the good part.</b> Find the few seconds where the move is at its most beautiful — the peak of the reveal, the heart of the orbit — and cut to that. A short, strong aerial beats a long, sagging one every time.</li>
  <li><b>Grade to match, don't grade in isolation.</b> Correct the aerial so its exposure, white balance, and contrast match the shots on either side of it. It should feel like the same film, not a postcard dropped into your movie.</li>
  <li><b>Pull back the drone "look."</b> Aerials often come in over-sharp and over-saturated. Soften the sharpening and tame the saturation so it blends with your ground footage's texture.</li>
  <li><b>Stabilize if needed.</b> A slightly bumpy move (from wind or a jerky input) can often be smoothed with warp/stabilization tools in the edit — a useful safety net, though never a substitute for flying smoothly.</li>
  <li><b>Speed-ramp with care.</b> Slowing an aerial slightly can make it more majestic and hide small wobbles; footage shot at a higher frame rate slows most cleanly. Use it deliberately, not on everything.</li>
  <li><b>Cut on motion.</b> Enter and exit aerials while the camera is moving, and let the move's own momentum carry into and out of the next shot — it makes the cut feel motivated rather than abrupt.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Make it disappear</h2>

<p>Here's the goal that ties this whole chapter together, and it's a little counterintuitive: <strong>the best drone footage in a finished film is invisible.</strong> Not literally — the shot is right there on screen — but invisible in the sense that the audience never stops to think "that's a drone shot." They just feel the scale, the movement, the emotion, and stay inside the film. The moment a viewer consciously registers the aerial as a technique, you've broken the spell, and the two things that most often break it are exactly the two we've been fixing: an aerial that runs too long and starts to sag, and an aerial whose color doesn't match the film so it reads as a stock clip. Both are edit problems, and both are solvable. Trim every aerial to only its strongest few seconds so it never overstays its welcome; grade every aerial to sit inside the film's look so it never feels imported. When you do, the drone shot does its emotional job — the awe of the reveal, the sweep of the transition, the smallness of the character against the landscape — without ever raising its hand to say "look at me, I'm a drone." This is the same restraint from the last chapter, applied one level down: it's not just about using aerials sparingly, it's about finishing the ones you do use so they belong. Get this right and you complete the whole arc of this course. You chose the right drone, learned the law, learned to fly smoothly, mastered the moves and settings, shot with composition and light, used aerials with narrative purpose, and now you finish them so seamlessly that they simply become part of the film. That's the mark of a real aerial cinematographer: not the flashiest footage, but footage so well-flown, well-chosen, and well-finished that it vanishes into the story it serves.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The best drone footage in a finished film is invisible — the audience feels the scale and emotion but never stops to think "that's a drone shot."</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>In the edit, I do two things to every aerial without fail: I cut it down to the few seconds where the move truly sings, and I grade it to match the shots around it. Those two moves are the difference between a drone shot that feels like part of my film and one that feels like a beautiful postcard someone slid into the middle of it. When I get it right, nobody watching ever says "nice drone shot" — they just stay in the story. That silence, that lack of comment, is the whole goal. Make the aerial disappear into the film, and you've done the job.</p>
</div>`,
